Loses the Rook instantly. It looks like the Knight is covering b1 as well as the Rook but it can cover only one of those two. Qxe4 and Knigt can not take back because of checkmate on b1. 26...., Rb1. 27. Nxb1, Qxe4. 28. Qe2 , Kh8. 29. Qd2 defends d4 and checkmate on e1. This is the worst case expected by white....

29...., Nb8! Saves the pawn and white's Queen is not very active anymore. Black should be looking for time to win white's knight at f1 by playing Queen and Rook. What can white do, 30. d5!? or 30. g3. In any case 30...., Qd3 will be a good move for black, aiming for Rb1 to look for the Knight or alternatively to look for a Queen's exchange on a6.
